<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100592124194120></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100592124194120><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=93845&mid=100592124194120>In the Gorge - Ch. 2: An Army of Two</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=93845&mid=100592124194120#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Scholar>Arjaizen</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>65 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Nov 16th 9:34 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>"By the Stormkeeper, I think I've had enough blessings for one day," Barrik grumbled.  The clouds had rolled in shortly after he left Rivervale, and the rain had been coming down in torrents ever since.  The followers of Karana, of which Barrik was one, believed in the power of storms, and that rain brought life.  As such, storms were a blessing from their god.  The soaked ranger was all but completely waterlogged at this point however.  His cup was quite literally running over, and he was beginning to think there was such a thing as too many blessings.<br><br>In the dimming light, he was able to make out a small goblin encampment, and the cave entrance to Runnyeye Citadel.  He would need to sneak through there to get to the Gorge of King Xorbb.  Casting a spell of camouflage, he slowly snuck up on the goblin sentries, who he heard talking to each other in some incomprehensible tongue.  He was hard-pressed to think of another sound quite like it.  Gently flicking a pebble down the hill, he caused the sentries to both dash down to investigate.  While they did so, he quickly slipped past, into the goblin stronghold.<br><br>More horrific sounds reached his ears as he made his way through the caves of Runnyeye.  Screams, spell invocations, and the unmistakable squishing sound of the floating evil eyes.   He did not know why they chose, for the most part, to stay within the confines of Runnyeye and the Gorge, but it was something for which he was grateful.<br><br>By the time he had made it out the back entrance and into the gorge itself, night had fallen, and the rain had thankfully ended.  It had been a long, tiring trek, and he wanted to make camp and get some rest.  The problem was one of where to make his camp where he could hopefully remain undisturbed.  A short search brought him to a small cleft in the rock, in which he saw a small, well-hidden fire.  Tending the fire was a young half-elf in banded armor.<br><br>"Hail, brother," he called quietly. "I am Barrik Moonhunter, a ranger of the 7th Legion, and servant to Karana."<br><br>"Well met, Barrik Moonhunter. I am Marchant Braemar, paladin to Mithaniel Marr," came the reply.  "Would you care to partake of my fire?"<br><br>"Gladly, and many thanks."  Barrik sat down and pulled a small pot from his pack.  As the paladin looked on, he started to make some soup from foraged roots, meat, and vegetables.  As he waited for the pot to boil, he noticed Marchant repairing his armor. <br><br>"You do that with great skill," he observed.  "Are you perchance a blacksmith?"<br><br>"Yes," came the response. "I try to rely on my own abilities and the blessings of my god as much as possible.  I do not wish to be beholden to others."  He pointed out the rest of his armor.  "I made all of this myself."<br><br>"As for myself, I am a fletcher," Barrik offered.  He handed his carved elm bow to Marchant.  "This is an example of my work.  I could make you one, if you wish."<br><br>Marchant shook his head. "No, a bow would not be an honorable weapon for me.  I prefer to fight my enemies face-to-face."<br><br>Barrik cocked an eyebrow. "Any weapon that aids in the destruction of evil is honorable to me.  In any case, it's hard to hunt with a sword," he added with a grin.<br><br>A look of amusement came across the paladin's face, and he chuckled.  "True enough.  I never thought of that.  So what brings you to the Beholder's Maze, Barrik?"<br><br>"The halflings of Rivervale have asked for help fighting against the minotaurs, who have allied themselves with the goblins of Runnyeye.  They can handle the goblins, but are concerned the minotaurs may breach the Thicket wall.  I'm here to stop them from getting there."<br><br>"Alone? I would think that would be quite a challenge," Marchant observed. "Even for a Legionnaire."<br><br>"Well, I do have a partner in the fight," Barrik answered, as he offered Marchant some soup, and served himself some as well.  "He will not be able to join me until after the morrow.  He's still recovering from injuries from our last sojourn here.  I may be unable to do more than scout the area and pick off a single minotaur here and there."<br><br>Marchant thought about that, and his face steeled with resolve.  "No, I think you'll be able to do more than that."  He extended his hand towards the Legionnaire. "Your task is an honorable one.  I have a mission elsewhere, but it can wait for a short time.  If you wish, I will join you until your friend returns."<br><br>Barrik grasped the offered hand and shook it.  "I would be honored by your company, good paladin.  We should rest for now.  Tomorrow will be a busy day."<br><br>Together, they quickly cleaned up from their brief repast, and prepared to sleep.  Marchant took the first watch.  Exhaustion took hold of Barrik, and he quickly fell into a sound sleep.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>21st Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Centurion Politico, 7th Legion</td></tr>
