<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100592088195038></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100592088195038><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=93845&mid=100592088195038>In the Gorge - Ch. 1: Lone Departure</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=93845&mid=100592088195038#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Scholar>Arjaizen</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>65 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Nov 16th 9:28 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Rising at the break of dawn comes naturally to those who call themselves rangers. In this, Barrik was no different from his brethren. He awoke as the sun's rays entered the window of his room, washed his face in the basin and quickly dressed.<br><br>Breakfast was simple, but hearty, as was his habit. Boiled milled grain with some dried fruit and honey satisfied his hunger, and he returned to his room to finish equipping his weapons and supplies. <br><br>Before leaving Rivervale, he looked in on his friend and compatriot Cona, who though he had already tended to his own wounds, would still need a day or so for the bones in his leg to fully knit. It seemed there were limits to what even the big shaman's skills could repair... Sometimes one still needed to rest.<br><br>Not that Cona wanted to admit it. "I'm fine, ready to go," he growled impatiently as he pushed aside his breakfast tray and tried to get up. <br><br>He almost made it all the way to his feet. Unfortunately, he neglected to consider the low ceiling of the halfling built inn. Hitting his head caused a sudden change in direction (from up to down,) and startled him to the point of making it impossible for him to hide the pain in his leg. Though it wasn't much, the wince on Cona's face was tantamount to a scream of agony from the normally stoic barbarian.<br><br>"Oh get back in bed, you're not fooling anyone," Barrik chided. "Next time a minotaur throws a boulder the size of a troll's head at you, just remember that trying to catch it and throw it back is probably not your best option."<br><br>"Hah!" Cona retorted. "The look of surprise on his face would have been worth it!"<br><br>Barrik considered that. "True," he admitted, "'would have been,' being the key."<br><br>The big shaman waved dismissively at his friend. "You have no sense of style," he grunted.<br><br>"I don't care about style. Right now, I care about dead minotaurs. Besides, style got you a broken leg, and two days in bed even after healing."<br><br>Cona feigned disgust and rolled over. "If you're going to give council like an old woman, I'm going back to sleep."<br><br>"And the light of reason dawns," Barrik teased. "Rest today. Head to the Gorge tomorrow. I'll meet you near the entrance to Runnyeye in two days time."<br><br>"Fine, off with you," the barbarian grumbled. "Try not to get eaten by goblins."<br><br>Barrik ducked out the door and left the inn, heading to the tunnel through the mountains that led to the Misty Thicket. Glancing skyward, he gauged the height of the sun. He would need to hurry to make it to the Gorge by nightfall. With grim determination he set out.  In the distance, black clouds rimmed the horizon, harbingers of things to come.<br>&nbsp;<br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>21st Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Centurion Politico, 7th Legion</td></tr>
