<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100591996394185></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100591996394185><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=93845&mid=100591996394185>In the Gorge - Prologue: Making the Rounds</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=93845&mid=100591996394185#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Scholar>Arjaizen</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>65 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Nov 16th 9:12 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The sun was dropping between two peaks of the High Pass range as the young wood elf druid entered the gates of High Keep. Young being a relative term. The grandparents of the human Keep guards had not even been born when Mayne Ringjumper completed her first season of training. To their eyes, she appeared to be no older than twenty years. Yet for all her apparent youthfulness, there was a look in her expression that told the guards she was not one to trifle with. They silently kept their vigil as she walked past.<br><br>Mayne shook the dust of three continents from her cloak as she settled into her room at the inn. After a good meal and a hot bath, the chill had left her bones (the wind cutting through the pass was especially cold that afternoon.) Wrapped in a warm robe the innkeeper had provided, she poured herself a small glass of wine, and sat in a cushioned chair to read the reports she had gathered from the 7th Legion members throughout Norrath.<br><br>The first rays of the sun hit her eyes as dawn broke, waking her from a sound sleep. She looked down and saw the reports on the floor, the wine barely touched. "I should have known better," she thought. "These things always put me to sleep. At least the chair was comfortable."<br><br>After breakfast, she sought out Barrik Moonhunter, the Legionnaire assigned to the High Pass area. He hadn't been there the night before, and the night clerk didn't know his whereabouts. There was a different clerk there in the morning, and she decided to try again, hoping for better luck.<br><br>"Mr. Moonhunter?", the clerk asked. "He left yesterday morning with that Barbarian he hangs around with, said he likely wouldn't be back for a while." Noticing the Legion insignia on her cloak's clasp, he asked," You in the 7th Legion? He said someone from his guild might come lookng for him."<br><br>"Yes," Mayne replied. "My name is Mayne. Did he leave anything to pass on to the Legion?"<br><br>"He sure did, got it right here." Unlocking a heavy iron chest, the clerk pulled out an envelope, sealed with a symbol of a bow and arrow crossed over a cresent moon. He handed it to Mayne, who gave him a silver piece for his trouble.<br><br>"Thanks. I'll be back," she said over her shoulder as she went back to her room. Once there, she opened the envelope and examined the letter inside.<br><br>___<br><br>To: Council of Ten, 7th Legion<br>From: Barrik Moonhunter<br>Re: Status Report, High Pass<br><br>Councilors:<br><br>Activity of gnoll and orc populations in the area seems well in hand. A goodly number of adventurers and mercenaries has been keeping the vermin from endangering the residents of the pass and keep unduly. There is not a great deal I can add to their efforts.<br><br>The Mayor of Rivervale has sent a messenger to the Keep, seeking assistance. Runnyeye goblins have been terrorizing the halflings of late, and apparently have found allies in the minotaurs of the nearby Gorge of King Xorbb, which is known by some as the Beholder's Maze. <br><br>The halflings believe they can defend themselves against the goblins, but need the minotaurs stopped, as they believe the minotaurs may be able to breach the protective wall guarding the Misty Thicket. To that end, My compatriot Cona and I have agreed to travel to the gorge and attempt to halt the invasion of the great horned monstrosities. <br><br>By your leave, for the forseeable future I will make my base in Rivervale, though I have left word with the Bards of the Keep as to my whereabouts should my presence be required there.<br><br>It is my belief the danger to Rivervale is pressing, whilst High Pass at present seems in safe hands. Should the judgement of the council or the Caesar be otherwise, I submit myself to your justice.<br><br>In service to Karana, I remain,<br><br>Barrik Moonhunter, Legionary<br>C/O League of Antonican Bards, Rivervale<br><br>___<br><br>Mayne placed the report with the others, and jotted down a note supporting the judgement of the Half-elf ranger. (Being Consul of State, she felt safe speaking for the council.) She gave it to the clerk as she checked out of the inn, and exited the gates of the High Keep. Summoning the forces of nature about her, she opened a gate to another part of the world. "Next stop, Toxxulia Forest," she called out to the young guard at the gate, "Serving Erudin, Paineel, Erud's Crossing, and Kerra Island. Keep your feet inside the gate, and please don't feed the kobolds."<br><br>The guard looked at her, head cocked to one side. As the shimmering gate closed about her, she gave him a mischevous grin and a wink. With a bright flash, she was gone, leaving behind only a twinkling of light, and the echoes of her laughter.<br><br>-----<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>21st Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Centurion Politico, 7th Legion</td></tr>
