<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100584021370046></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100584021370046><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=93845&mid=100584021370046>Gossip in the Barracks</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=93845&mid=100584021370046#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Scholar>Arjaizen</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>65 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Nov 15th 11:03 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Note:<br><br>The 7th Legion's command structure is much like the Roman military.  The leader of the guild is called the Caesar, or occasionally, Elder.  The officers are called Centurions, and each has his or her own area of responsibility - recruiter, jurist, politico, et cetera.  At the time of this writing, the Caesar of the 7th Legion was Fortenbras Oberonis, a Shaman of Halas.<br><br>------------<br><br>The door to the 7th Legion soldier's barracks opened, and a cold blast of frigid air followed.  A hooded man in a white, ice-encrusted bearskin cloak stood framed in the doorway.  As Scei and Gilgazin looked up from their drinks at the great table, he closed the door behind him, and hung the cloak on a wooden peg on the wall, revealing himself to be a slightly-built Erudite in brown robes.<br><br>"What's the matter, you two?" Arjaizen grinned.  "Did you get kicked out of every tavern in Halas?"<br><br>"Arj!" Scei shouted.  "What're you doing back here?  I thought you were in Freeport."<br><br>"I was," Arjaizen admitted. "But I grew tired of that place.  It's too hot, too dry, and too crowded.  I'm not sure where I'm going to go next.  Perhaps back to Erudin for a while.  It's been a long time since I was home.<br><br>"So why are you two here instead of out on the town?"<br><br>Scei grinned, and hoisted her flagon.  "No need.  Gil got a care package from Kaladim.  Dwarven Ripple!"<br><br>"Ah, I see.  Don't pay for what you can get for free." Arjaizen replied, turning to the young Dwarf.  "So, good cleric, do you think you might spare a drop for a chilled comrade-in-arms?"<br><br>"Glad ta, my friend," Gilgazin offered cheerily.  "Got plenty ta go 'round."<br><br>As he poured a flagon of the strong Dwarven brew, he asked, "Hey, 'd you two hear 'bout Amberrious?  Seems some wizard sent a letter to the Caesar, saying he oughtta be reprimanded fer bein' rough with him."<br><br>"Amberrious?  The paladin?"  Arjaizen looked astounded. "I find that hard to believe.  There must be more to the story."<br><br>"Sure is," Gilgazin agreed. "The wizard made fun 'o his name.  Said it was funny soundin', or sumthin' like that.  Then, he sez in th' letter that Amberrious was angry and threatnin'."<br><br>"And this came as a surprise?  Such that he deemed it necessary to complain to the Caesar himself?" Arjaizen asked.<br><br>"Musta been an Erudite," Scei muttered into her drink.  "Buncha prisses make High Elves seem like tavern wenches."  She looked at Arjaizen.  "No offense."<br><br>"None taken, my dear," Arjaizen answered.  "I am well aware that my brethren can be somewhat lacking in social graces, and that they often believe an air of haughty superiority will give them the appearance of intellectual agility."<br><br>"Yeah," Scei replied, wiping her mouth on her sleeve.  "And they think bein' rude makes 'em look smart, too."<br><br>"Indeed," the Erudite grinned.<br><br>"Tell me Arj," Gilgazin asked, "Do ya think Elder Fortenbras'll come down on Amberrious?"<br><br>Arjaizen shook his head.  "If the story is as simple as you say, I doubt it.  If what you say is true, the young wizard apparently admitted he started the whole thing.  How foolish must one be to insult the name of a stranger?  After doing so, what kind of reaction was he expecting?"<br><br>Scei belched loudly. "Amberrious should've punched his lights out.  I would've."<br><br>"And therein lies the warrior's charm, my dear," Arjaizen smiled, sipping his drink.  "But paladins are held to a more... restrained standard.  I suspect he has more to worry about from his order than from the Guild."<br><br>"So, my friends, tell me what else has been going on in Halas since I left..."<br><br>As the fire burned and the drink flowed, the conversation went long into the night...<br>&nbsp;<br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>21st Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Centurion Politico, 7th Legion</td></tr>
